texts:
This year we are excited to expand our EdVentures program beyond Bellingham city limits! We are currently also serving Mount Baker School District and looking to expand into Blaine School District as well!

Our series of outings for 1st, 2nd, and 3rd grade classrooms focus on topics ranging from bird nests to pollinators and align with Next Generation Science Standards.

We are excited to have strong support from Mount Baker School District leadership. Curriculum Director, Bridget Rossman, has said, "As a rural school district encompassing 622 square miles, surrounded by forest, rivers, and mountains, we believe in the power of our outdoor classroom yet lack the expertise to fully utilize it.

We are thrilled to partner with community organizations to provide outdoor, educational lessons that integrate healthy habits, scientific inquiry, and social-emotional learning."

We are excited to be outside with more students this year! If you'd like to help support our EdVentures program you can donate by clicking the link in our bio.

#blaineschooldistrict  #mountbakerschooldistrict #communityorganizations

texts:
Tonight @le_gafa is proud to share table sponsorship alongside alumni and actor/writer @ericscanlanjr & community partner @pacbizorg in support of the highly anticipated @wearesamoagala 

ABOUT THE EVENT
The We Are Samoa Gala is proud to be a platform that will benefit several initiatives that will serve the Pacific Islander Community through general education scholarships, performing arts scholarships, and continuing to build awareness on the burden of type 2 diabetes and heart disease on the Pacific Islander community.

• General education scholarships for Pacific Islanders students (through the National Pacific Islander Network, 501c3) 
• The Jerome Grey Performing Arts Fund to support Pacific Islander students pursuing a career in the arts 
• Create awareness and build outreach programs for the Pacific Islander community on the importance of the burden of diabetes on our community

Do you know exactly HOW you'll create the change in your community you want to see? How do you go from vision, to reality? 

All the great ideas you have in your mind can only become a reality in your community if you have an ACTIONABLE plan. 

What's your plan look like for this year?

Maybe you feel like the last few years of COVID set you back in what you had planned. I still believe that a strategic plan is exactly what you need to overcome those setbacks. 

I created a FREE webinar you can sign up for to learn more about how strategic planning can help you move forward this year, even if you've experienced set backs. 

Click the link in my bio to learn more and sign up.

texts:
Unfortunately, there is no cookie cutter recipe for designing a successful social movement that brings about institutional change. Scholars throughout the world have tried to delineate some essential elements but, to this day, disagree on many of them.  Although there is no consensus, there are many plausible theories that explain these social phenomena that are proliferating now, more than ever before.
 
Today, I want to highlight one perspective in particular, formulated by Erica Chenoweth, political  science professor at Harvard University. After looking over hundreds of social and political campaigns for the past century, she suggested that for a social movement to be truly influential it has to yield almost immediate results, be generally peaceful, and engage at least 3.5% of the population.
 
Do you agree or disagree?
 
Source: The '3.5% rule': How a small minority can change the world, BBC, May 2019
 
#socialmovements #communication #communicationstudies #blm #meetoo #socialchange #socialtheory #culture #harvard #minorities #protests #law #politics #peacefulprotest #blog #bbcnews #bbc

Arizonans are tired of Senator Sinema’s excuses, and it shows. Sinema’s favorability rating dropped drastically after she took her vocal position in favor of the Senate filibuster rule—and Arizonans are not happy. 

Sinema’s support for the filibuster will jeopardize almost every piece of popular legislation on the agenda—from protection for our right to vote to immigration reform to worker protections.

Arizonans, including Democrats and Independents aren’t standing for it. It’s time for Sinema to listen to her constituents if she wants to save her political reputation. Click the link in our bio or visit bit.ly/SinemaSinks to read our latest blog on Sinema’s drop in favorability, and why Sen. Kelly isn’t suffering the same fate.

Congratulations to #Marsiling grassroots patron, Ignatius Francis Danakody, PBM who received the National Day Public Service Award last weekend.

Serving Marsiling CCC as one of our patrons, he works closely with the committee to assess the needs of various initiatives to contribute regularly to welfare funds. These funds have been meaningfully utilized to benefit the less fortunate residents in Marsiling. It supports the various welfare initiatives in Marsiling, such as the youths' mentorship program, monthly grocery distribution to residents, and festive hongbao distribution.

I am thankful for volunteers such as Ignatius for their generous contribution, enabling us to carry out programmes that benefit our residents.

Marketing is the conversation between a brand and its audience. It shouldn't feel like a gimmick or a "gotcha!" It should be a sharing of values - a relationship built on trust. 

For a locally owned business, marketing is the chance to get to know the people who make that lifestyle possible <U+0001F44B><U+0001F44B><U+0001F44B>

Happy Women's History Month!

Our celebration of Women's History Month will feature inspirational women in Hawaii to showcase the impact they have made in our community.

Today, we are featuring Pasty T. Mink! 

Pasty was the first woman of color, and the first Asian American elected to Congress. She also authored Title IX, a law that bans gender discrimination among federally-funded education programs. 

Mahalo to Patsy Mink for her dedication and services!
.
.
.

texts:
Congratulations to our #Marsiling grassroots leader, Kenny Chua PBM, who received the National Day Public Service Award from President Halimah Yacob last weekend.

Compassionate and kind-hearted, Kenny has been an excellent role model to our Marsiling residents and friends. He has been serving since 2013, and was Marsiling Zone 4 RN Chairman appointed in 2016. He has led by example to guide RN members to provide care for residents, conduct house visits, and help create a vibrant social environment through various activities and courses.

Under his leadership, members are motivated to serve the community with passion. He has pleasant and easy-going character, which helps build meaningful connections with residents. Residents are often at ease in approaching him whenever they require assistance, knowing that they can rely on the grassroots to go the extra mile to assist them. 

Kenny is truly a dedicated grassroots leader who has devoted much of his available time to the community, and we are greatly appreciative of his efforts. 

Once again, thank you for your dedication to Zone 4 RN and Marsiling community.

#marsiling #grassroots #congratulations #achievement #welldeserved #achievementaward #awardwinners #motivational #team #motivation

texts:
Most Americans probably don't know a lot about a rule in the U.S. Senate known as the "filibuster," but they should. Why? As was made painfully clear during FRC's Pray Vote Stand broadcast last night, the filibuster is the only thing standing in the way of America ceasing to be the free country that we know and love due to the disturbing policies that the extreme Left wants to force through the Senate and impose on all Americans without compromise.<U+2060>
<U+2060>
In a country that is politically split down the middle, collaboration and dialogue is what we need more of, not less of. Even so, more and more politicians on the Left are hypocritically calling for an end to the filibuster now that they have the slimmest possible majority in the Senate, even though the Left has been using the filibuster to their advantage for over 200 years whenever they weren't in the majority.<U+2060>
<U+2060>
It used to be that the Senate required an even higher bar to pass legislation—a two-thirds majority to end debate, instead of the 60 votes they changed it to in 1975. Now, instead of working to find middle ground, Democrats want to blow up the entire system and let a simple majority rule. But that's not what the founders intended. They wanted conversation, give-and-take, and cooperation. And if unity is what Joe Biden's party actually wants, then silencing the minority party is hardly the best way to go about it.<U+2060>
<U+2060>
Wednesday, one of the moderate Democrats holding the line on the filibuster, Senator Kyrsten Sinema (D-Ariz.) told the Wall Street Journal, "When you have a place that's broken and not working, and many would say that's the Senate today, I don't think the solution is to erode the rules. I think the solution is for senators to change their behavior and begin to work together, which is what the country wants us to do."<U+2060>
<U+2060>
Continue reading at the link in bio.<U+2060>
<U+2060>

texts:
RWOP's Charity of the Month for April is Yavapai Casa for Kids. 
<U+200B>
This foundation serves the needs of abused, neglected and abandoned children who are in the care of the Yavapai County Prescott Court, and also youth who are enrolled in the Department of Child Safety Foster Care Program.

CASA stands for Court Appointed Special Advocates. Participants are local volunteers who have been certified by the Arizona Supreme Court to serve the best best interests of abused and neglected children. That includes providing a safe, nurturing and permanent home for them. The CASA for Kids Foundation assists these foster families with needed items they may not be able to afford, such as clothing, toys, blankets, school supplies and more.

Please help out this worthy cause with a generous donation of your time or money. Volunteers are always in demand. All donations are eligible under the Arizona Tax Credit program. Anything you can do will be greatly appreciated.

VISIT https://yavapaicasaforkids.org/ FOR MORE INFO. 
.
.
.
